{
  "texts": [
    "Ngai et al.'s (2011) literature analysis indicates that logistic models, neural networks, Bayesian belief networks, and decision trees are the most often employed strategies for detecting fraud.",
    "The research examines four categories of fraud, namely those in banking, insurance, securities, and commodities, but it provides neither a comprehensive understanding of fraud nor explains how the models could detect the fraud.",
    "Chang and Chang (2012) present a cost-effective method for early identification of online auction fraud.",
    "This study's focus is limited to online auction fraud, yet the proposed model does not demonstrate that it can also be utilized to detect other unknown facts.",
    "Another study, Ahmed et al. (2016), provides a comprehensive overview of several clustering approaches for detecting anomalies and comparing methodologies."
  ]
}